docs.snippet: Charles Blow, Roxane Gay and Esau McCaulley join Lulu Garcia-Navarro to discuss why the incident has elicited so many passionate responses.
docs.lead_paragraph: Will Smith’s slap has already launched a thousand takes. On Sunday evening at the Academy Awards, the actor struck Chris Rock after the comedian joked about his wife’s shaved head. (Jada Pinkett Smith has alopecia, a condition that leads to hair loss.) Later in the evening, when Smith won his first Oscar, he apologized onstage, saying, “Love will make you do crazy things.”

headline.main: Four Opinion Writers on Will Smith’s Slap: ‘There Are No Heroes in This Story’

docs.abstract: The heroine of Kate Chopin’s “The Awakening” begins to notice what she wants, rather than what her male-dominated society wants her to want.
docs.snippet: The heroine of Kate Chopin’s “The Awakening” begins to notice what she wants, rather than what her male-dominated society wants her to want.
docs.lead_paragraph: Early in “The Awakening” — Kate Chopin’s great feminist novel of identity and self-consciousness, which still throbs with relevance more than 120 years after its publication — the heroine’s husband picks a fight. He has spent the evening at a casino and now it’s approaching midnight, but the card game has left Léonce “in high spirits, and very talkative.” He wakes his wife to gossip but she answers him sleepily, “with little half utterances.” Spurned, and still intent on rousing her, Léonce manufactures a fever for their sleeping son. When Edna dares doubt this, Léonce calls her a bad mother. She springs out of bed to check, while Léonce — no longer worried, if he ever actually was — enjoys his cigar. Soon, Mr. Pontellier is fast asleep, but “Mrs. Pontellier was by that time thoroughly awake.”

headline.main: The Classic Novel That Saw Pleasure as a Path to Freedom

docs.lead_paragraph: Shahawar Matin Siraj first met the older man late in the summer of 2003. He would see him at the mosque in Bay Ridge, Brooklyn, sobbing loudly during prayers and hovering near the imam. But when the man entered the bookstore nearby, where Siraj worked, he was warm and easygoing. He said his name was Osama Eldawoody, and the two men struck up an unlikely friendship.
